---
// v60c — Hornbook card enriched (first-draft scope + citation-verification
// process); "Published & companion works" moved to the Reading Room's
// published shelf (/reading/#published-shelf) — the Writing Room is for
// works being written. Earlier: v60b surfaced the three migrated books
// alongside the AI-governance essay; books are the headline, open essays
// sit beneath as their own section.
import RoomLayout from '../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';
---
<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="Writing Room"
  subtitle="First drafts, comments, coauthors."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="writing-index"
>
  <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p>
      The Writing Room is where the Library's authors compose drafts in
      the open. The book-length manuscripts the Library is assembling live
      here, alongside the legal hornbook and open essays addressed to
      specific audiences. Finished editorial pieces graduate to
      <a href="/voices/">Voices</a> when they ship; published scholarship
      and curated primary sources live in the <a href="/reading/">Reading
      Room</a>'s catalog next door.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is unusual. Most publishing institutions show only finished
      work; the process by which finished work gets made stays hidden.
      The Library publishes the process too, because the
      cognitive-partnership thesis the project partly advances depends
      on the partnership being visible. Two and a half centuries of
      school-trust history make plain that institutions which conceal
      their working are institutions that drift; institutions whose
      working is in the open are institutions a watchful crew can
      defend.
    </p>

    <p>
      Drafts here are real drafts — not procedural placeholders. They
      argue, they cite, they make their case. They are also incomplete,
      sometimes wrong in detail, and openly seeking comment. If you
      read something here and see a mistake, an omission, or a sharper
      version of the argument, write to the
      <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>. If you have
      substrate the draft would benefit from — a court opinion, a state
      report, a primary-source document — send it. The Writing Room
      exists because the work the Library is doing is bigger than any
      one author can produce alone.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="hornbook mt-10" aria-labelledby="hornbook-heading">
    <h2 id="hornbook-heading" class="section-heading">The legal hornbook</h2>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">Law desk · First draft, under citation verification</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/hornbook/"><em>School Trust Lands: The Law of America's Educational Land Trusts</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">America's School Trust Library · A hornbook of school-trust law</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        A one-volume hornbook of school-trust law: granting instruments,
        the trust-character question, fiduciary duties, dispositions and
        full value, accounting, standing, remedies, and modern reform.
        The complete first draft is here — nineteen chapters plus state
        appendices, about 83,000 words — written against primary sources.
        Citations not yet verified are carried as visible
        <code>[VERIFY]</code> flags, and those flags are being resolved
        continuously: a background harvest pulls the cited opinions from
        CourtListener, and each claim is checked against the actual
        opinion text.
      </p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/hornbook/" class="card-cta">Open the hornbook →</a>
        <a href="/for-lawyers/" class="card-cta">Lawyer on-ramp →</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="books mt-10" aria-labelledby="books-heading">
    <h2 id="books-heading" class="section-heading">The three books</h2>

    <p class="section-intro">
      The Library is assembling three book-length works that tell the
      school-trust story in three tenses. <em>The Forgotten Forever Gift to Public Schools</em>
      is the <strong>past</strong>: how the United States built, kept, and
      broke a national endowment for public education across 235 years.
      <em>Who Steals from Children</em> is the <strong>present</strong>:
      the fight as it is being waged right now, state by state, beginning
      with Oregon and the Elliott — a case in court today. <em>Stewards of
      the Republic</em> is the <strong>future</strong>: how the people who
      already own this fight, and the architects of the AI-era forever-trusts
      now arriving, should build institutions that last. The first and third
      are the two volumes of <em>A Forever Gift</em> — Looking Back and
      Looking Forward; the second is the movement's living field record.
    </p>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The past · Looking back</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/schools-of-the-republic/"><em>The Forgotten Forever Gift to Public Schools</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Margaret Bird and Dave Sullivan · A Forever Gift, Book One</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        How the United States built — and largely lost — a national
        endowment for public education. A behavior-driven history (the
        inheritance, the trust kept, the trust broken, the trust rebuilt)
        followed by a state-by-state encyclopedia of all fifty.
      </p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/schools-of-the-republic/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/schools-of-the-republic-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest full draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The present · In court now</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/who-steals-from-children/"><em>Who Steals from Children: Volume 1 — Oregon and the Elliott</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · Reader's Edition</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        A first-person, scene-grounded account of how the State of Oregon
        has spent thirty-five years removing a billion-dollar working trust
        asset from the Common School Fund. The case is in court today; this
        volume is the evidence.
      </p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/who-steals-from-children/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/who-steals-from-children-vol1-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest full draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The future · Looking forward</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/eighth-anchor/"><em>Stewards of the Republic</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · A Forever Gift, Book Two · First draft, 2026</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        Defending the forever gift in the age of artificial intelligence.
        How the people who already hold this inheritance — trustees,
        advocates, teachers, parents — build the coalition, the shared
        Library, and the electronic tools that let a watchful public defend
        a trust in real time; and what that record offers the architects of
        the new perpetual institutions now being chartered. Formerly titled
        <em>The Eighth Anchor</em>.
      </p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/eighth-anchor/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/stewards-of-the-republic-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest full draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <p class="mt-10 text-sm italic text-slate-500">
    Finished works have moved to the
    <a href="/reading/#published-shelf">Reading Room shelf →</a>
    (<em>Oregon's Constitutional Duties to Schools</em>,
    <em>Great Fires</em>, <em>Caulked Boots and Cheese Sandwiches</em>).
  </p>

  <section class="essays mt-10" aria-labelledby="essays-heading">
    <h2 id="essays-heading" class="section-heading">Open essays</h2>

    <article class="essay-card">
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/the-only-forever-trust/">"The Only Forever-Trust We Have Data On"</a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · May 2026 · ~2,350 words · Working draft</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        A focused essay taking the eight-anchor school-trust-failure-modes
        argument directly to AI-governance designers building the next
        century's perpetual institutions. Comments welcome.
      </p>
    </article>

    <p class="mt-6 text-sm italic text-slate-500">
      More essays as they reach working-draft form. If you're interested
      in being a named correspondent for a Writing Room draft — an
      early reader whose comments shape the final version — write to
      the <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</RoomLayout>

<style>
  .section-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .book-card,
  .essay-card {
    background: var(--linen-card, #fafaf7);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-border, #e5e7eb);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 1.5rem 1.5rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .card-kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .card-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    line-height: 1.35;
    margin: 0 0 0.4rem;
  }
  .card-title a {
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .card-title a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .card-byline {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: #475569;
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
  }
  .card-blurb {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #334155;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .card-cta {
    align-self: flex-start;
    color: #1d4ed8;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }
  .card-cta:hover {
    color: #1e40af;
  }
  .card-cta-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.25rem 1.5rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .card-cta-row .card-cta {
    align-self: auto;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .card-bridge {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: #64748b;
    font-style: italic;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0;
  }
  .card-bridge a {
    color: #475569;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .section-intro {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #334155;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
</style>
